04187nam a22005895i 9780804766890DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222003cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047668907 a10.1515/97808047668902doi  a(DE-B1597)581822  a(OCoLC)1312726708  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aP95.55b.F413 2003 7aLAN0000002bisacsh04a306.441 aFelman, Shoshana, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Scandal of the Speaking Body :bDon Juan with J. L. Austin, or Seduction in Two Languages /cShoshana Felman. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (176 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMeridian: Crossing Aesthetics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface to the New Edition -- tForeword to The Scandal of the Speaking Body -- tThe Scandal of the Speaking Body -- tPreface: The Promising Animal -- t1. Between Linguistics and Philosophy of Langauge: Theories of Promise, Promises of Theory -- t2. The Perversion of Promising: Don Juan and Literary Performance -- t3. The Scandal of the Performative -- t4. Knowledge and Pleasure, or the Philosopher’s Performance (Psychoanalysis and the Performative) -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tCrossing Aesthetics0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat is a promise? What are the consequences of the act of promising? In this bold yet subtle meditation, the author contemplates the seductive promise of speech and the seductive promise of love. Imagining an encounter between Molière’s Don Juan and J. L. Austin, between a mythical figure of the French classical theater and a twentieth-century philosopher, she explores the relation between speech and the erotic, using a literary text as the ground for a telling encounter between philosophy, linguistics, and Lacanian psychoanalytic theory. In the years since the publication of this book (which the author today calls “the boldest, the most provocative, but also the most playful” she has written), speech act theory has continued to play a central and defining role in the theories of sexuality, gender, performance studies, post-colonial studies, and cultural studies. This book remains topical as readers increasingly discover how multiply relevant the speaking body is. Moving beyond the domain of formal linguistic analysis to address these questions, the author has written a daring and seductive book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aComedy. 0aDon Juan (Legendary character) in literature. 0aPerformative (Philosophy). 0aSpeech acts (Linguistics). 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / General.2bisacsh1 aButler, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavell, Stanley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFelman, Shoshana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107042040 cprintz978080474452240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476689040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804766890423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804766890/original  a978-3-11-070420-4  Stanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles